# WHAT IT IS
#   Blaise is "the Pascal you love, reimagined for the modern
#   era" — a from-scratch Object Pascal compiler that drops three
#   decades of FPC + Delphi compatibility baggage in favor of a
#   single-language-mode, single-string-type, reified-generic,
#   ARC-by-default dialect that targets native code through QBE
#   (and eventually LLVM).  The compiler is fully self-hosting:
#   `scripts/fixpoint.sh` rebuilds the compiler with itself in
#   three stages (stage-1 → stage-2 SSA → stage-3 SSA) and
#   asserts that stage-2 == stage-3 byte-for-byte.  Default debug
#   format is OPDF (graemeg/opdebugger), with DWARF being
#   non-required.  Test suite (2,293 tests and growing) is
#   itself written in Blaise.
#
# CLI ARGUMENT GRAMMAR  (verbatim from `compiler/src/main/
#                       pascal/Blaise.pas` `procedure PrintUsage`
#                       extracted via `gh api repos/graemeg/
#                       blaise/contents/compiler/src/main/
#                       pascal/Blaise.pas`)
#
#   blaise --source <file.pas> --output <binary>
#   blaise --source <file.pas> --emit-ir
#
#   Native flags:
#     --source <PATH>                Pascal source file (the
#                                    program's main `.pas`)
#     --output <PATH>                Output binary path
#                                    (omitted when --emit-ir)
#     --unit-path <DIR>              Add directory to unit
#                                    search path  (repeatable —
#                                    can also be configured via
#                                    `unit-path=<dir>` lines in
#                                    blaise.cfg or
#                                    ~/.blaise.cfg)
#     --target <ID>                  Code generation target
#                                    (linux-x86_64 (default) |
#                                    macos-arm64)
#     --emit-ir                      Print QBE IR to stdout and
#                                    exit  (no binary produced)
#     --debug                        Enable runtime memory leak
#                                    reporting on exit
#     --debug-opdf                   Emit OPDF debug info as a
#                                    `.opdf.s` companion file
#                                    next to the output binary
#
#   FPC-compatibility query flags  (used by PasBuild and other
#                                   FPC-aware tooling to probe
#                                   the compiler before invoking
#                                   a full compile; emit a single
#                                   line + Halt(0)):
#     -iV                            Print the version that
#                                    PasBuild is expected to see
#                                    (currently `3.2.2`)
#     -iTP                           Print target processor
#                                    (currently `x86_64`)
#     -iTO                           Print target OS
#                                    (currently `linux`)
#
#   FPC-style positional / dash-prefix args  (consumed by
#                                              `ParseFPCArgs`
#                                              when `pasbuild
#                                              --fpc /path/to/
#                                              blaise <file.pas>`
#                                              is invoked; the
#                                              binary doubles
#                                              as a drop-in FPC
#                                              replacement):
#     -FE<DIR>                       Output directory
#     -Fu<PATH>                      Unit search path
#                                    (lowercase — repeatable)
#     -FU<PATH>                      Unit output directory
#     -o<NAME>                       Output binary name
#     -Mobjfpc                       Language mode (silently
#                                    accepted)
#     -O<N>                          Optimization level (silently
#                                    accepted; Blaise has its
#                                    own optimizer)
#     -g                             Enable debug info (mapped
#                                    to --debug-opdf)
#     -gl                            Enable line-number debug
#                                    info
#     -CX                            Smart linking
#     -d<DEFINE>                     Define a conditional symbol
#
# LANGUAGE-CORPUS POSITION
#   Blaise is the 179th programming language entry in this
#   completion corpus.  It joins Fusion (R984 178th), Aver
#   (R980 177th — R980 round-number commit landmark), Raven
#   (R976 176th), HydraScript (R972 175th), Lazurite (R968
